            <a class="name">wziard</a> 
           </div> 
           <p class="cmt_cnt">Good article, though I was hoping to find a few more options. I happen to be one of those looking for something else to move on to after a year of studying Chinese in China (2 in the U.S.) and by the summer, a year of teaching at various schools. As the article states though, most of the jobs other than teaching, business related or not, require at least 2 to 3 years of experience to even be considered. How does a recent graduate coming to China, with a decent handle of Chinese, but virtually zero relevant work experience compete for higher level jobs. Even finding lesser jobs that offer experience related to upper-level positions are limited within China. As an international relations major, positions in consulates or embassies are in my interest, but I would guess they are easily taken by the more qualified. ( I must admit I haven't really submitted a resume to any of these places yet). <br /> <br />I think the biggest issue for many, is the threat of losing your footing by returning to your home country if indeed you do want to work in China, or anywhere else in East-Asia for that matter. Particularly if you have spent a significant amount of time learning Chinese. Returning home on one hand might give you experience you need, but kill, or significantly hurt your Chinese on the other. Unless of course your job at home is directly related to it, which also might not be the easiest to find. Are serious companies going to want someone with 2 years experience editing magazines or playing jazz-flute 4 nights a week at the local pub, even if their Chinese was excellent and had good recommendations/contacts? I don't know, but I think I would be hesitant without evidence of legit experience. Therein lies my predicament anyways. </p> 
