           <p class="cmt_cnt">The article lacks of information and doesn't represent the real situation in China. There are lots of other jobs foreigners can do here that are not mentionned here. <br /> <br />I am really surprised the article doesn't mention sales executive positions. It is pretty easy to get a job in trading companies, and very often Chinese language is not required or just conversational skills. <br /> <br />Salary is often around 4000-5000 thousand for no or low experienced candidates but can rapidely increase according to your performance. <br /> <br />It is in my opinion easy to have good performances in Chinese companies and westerners' have better organisational skills and spend less time on QQ than their chinese workmates. <br /> <br />A list of jobs foreigners can apply to in China <br /> <br />For non chinese speakers: <br /> <br />- sales executive <br />- quality controler <br />- customer relationship (in 5 star hotels) <br />- steward for international airlines (Hainan Air for example) <br />- Tour guide for inbound tourism <br /> <br />For fluent Chinese speaker: <br /> <br />- all above listed jobs <br />- marketing <br />- consulting <br />- sales representative for foreign brands <br />- translater <br />- other jobs related to your degree <br /> <br /> <br />The best is therefore to invest on Chinese lessons. This can make a signifacant difference on your salary, and gives you more oportunities <br /></p> 
