            <a class="name">David</a> 
           </div> 
           <p class="cmt_cnt">Yes, there are many other types of jobs out there, but I think the problem is that obtaining a valid work visa is difficult for fresh graduates or for former English teachers in China who want to change careers but do not have the two years of relevant foreign work experience. At this point, I'm beginning to think that finding work in China outside of teaching English is nearly impossible for fresh graduates like myself unless I can start my own company here. Of course, you can work illegally using a tourist/business visa, but not only is it troublesome and expensive to extend the visa or make the trip to HK every 90 or 180 days, but also, it is no way to have a real career. If China is so protectionist of its entry-level labor market and making it impossible for foreigners to find entry-level jobs, I wish my country, U.S., would start to have the same policy towards Chinese citizens who work in the U.S. because all of them can legally do entry-level work in the U.S., and once they get enough experience and know-how, they will just go back to China and profit from America's lax visa policy to the detriment of American citizens in U.S. and those based in China. </p> 
           <div class="mes_right_tit"> 
            <div class="rep"> 
             <span class="Detail"><a href="http://comments.comments.comments.listings.answers.obs.echinacities.com/15459">Detail</a></span> &nbsp;&nbsp;
             <a href="javascript:;" data-id="15459" class="report-handler">Report Abuse</a> 
            </div> 
            <span class="time"><em>Apr 30, 2011 13:16</em> </span> 
           </div> 
          </div> 
         </div> 
